Universal human rights refer to the fundamental rights and freedoms that are entitled to every person, regardless of nationality, ethnicity, gender, religion, or any other status. These rights are intended to ensure dignity, equality, and justice for all individuals. The concept of universal human rights is enshrined in various international documents and treaties, with the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) being one of the most significant.  Adopted by the United Nations General Assembly in 1948, the UDHR outlines a broad range of rights, including:  Right to Life and Liberty: Everyone has the right to life, liberty, and security of person. Freedom from Torture: No one shall be subjected to torture or to cruel, inhuman, or degrading treatment or punishment. Right to a Fair Trial: Everyone is entitled to a fair and public hearing by an independent and impartial tribunal. Freedom of Speech: Everyone has the right to freedom of opinion and expression. Right to Privacy: No one shall be subjected to arbitrary interference with their privacy, family, home, or correspondence. Right to Education: Everyone has the right to education, which should be directed to the full development of the human personality. These rights are considered inalienable, meaning they cannot be taken away, and they apply to all people equally. While the UDHR sets forth these principles, the actual implementation and protection of human rights can vary significantly from country to country, and ongoing efforts are necessary to address violations and promote these fundamental freedoms globally.

Abstract  This white paper presents a proposal for the development and deployment of a wETH (Wrapped Ethereum) bridge dedicated to TBC (Tibia Coin in-game Currency), with the primary objective of enabling the community to leverage this innovative toolset. The proposed bridge is envisioned as a pivotal solution to address several pressing issues within the gaming ecosystem, particularly in the context of gold farming activities. By establishing on-chain liquidity, we aim to facilitate enhanced market dynamics, fostering lower prices, and unlocking opportunities for market resellers. Furthermore, this initiative has the potential to set new standards for blockchain integration in the gaming industry, thereby eliciting interest from influential stakeholders such as Cipsoft GmbH.  1. Introduction  In recent years, the intersection of blockchain technology and the gaming industry has provided unprecedented opportunities for innovation and value creation. The emergence of in-game economies and assets has led to the rise of activities like gold farming, wherein players generate substantial profits by accumulating and trading in-game assets. However, this burgeoning ecosystem faces several challenges, including limited liquidity, price instability, and inefficiencies in asset trading.  This white paper introduces a comprehensive solution to these issues by proposing the development of a wETH bridge dedicated to TBC. By doing so, we aim to create a robust foundation that empowers the gaming community to harness the full potential of blockchain technology.  2. The wETH Bridge for TBC  The proposed wETH bridge for TBC serves as a bridge between traditional in-game assets and the Ethereum blockchain. This bridge will facilitate the seamless conversion of in-game assets into wETH tokens, which are fully compatible with the Ethereum blockchain. This integration offers several key benefits:  Enhanced Liquidity: By allowing for the exchange of in-game assets for wETH, we will inject liquidity into the gaming ecosystem. This liquidity will empower players and market participants, leading to more dynamic and competitive pricing.  Strengthening the Role of Resellers: The introduction of a wETH bridge will create opportunities for resellers to thrive in the gaming economy. Marketplaces can emerge, where resellers can arbitrage between in-game assets and wETH, adding value to the ecosystem.  3. Potential Industry Standards  The proposed wETH bridge and associated tooling have the potential to become a benchmark for blockchain integration within the gaming industry. As more participants adopt these standards, a virtuous cycle of innovation and collaboration can ensue.  The adoption of such standards could garner interest from key industry stakeholders, including Cipsoft GmbH. The incorporation of on-chain standards into mainstream gaming by influential players like Cipsoft GmbH would signify a significant milestone, further legitimizing blockchain technology in the gaming world.  4. Conclusion  The development and deployment of a wETH bridge for TBC, along with the accompanying toolset, represents a crucial step forward in addressing the challenges faced by the gaming community, particularly in the context of gold farming and asset trading. By increasing liquidity, empowering resellers, and potentially setting new industry standards, this initiative aims to reshape the gaming ecosystem for the better. The support and collaboration of the community and industry leaders, such as Cipsoft GmbH, are instrumental in realizing this vision.  Disclaimer: This white paper serves as a proposal and does not constitute a binding commitment. The implementation of the wETH bridge and associated tooling is subject to technical feasibility and community consensus.

Tim Exile (or Exile) is the recording alias of Timothy Charles Shaw, a producer and performer of electronic music spanning drum and bass, IDM, breakcore and gabber.  A classically trained violinist, he began experimenting with electronic music aged 12, and gained his first drum and bass release in 1999. In the following years he released mostly for the legendary Moving Shadow imprint, and John B's Beta Recordings, having met John B at Durham. After the completion of his philosophy degree, he went on to study an MA in electroacoustic composition at Durham. Perhaps unsurprisingly, his drum and bass grew increasingly experimental, and his debut LP (Pro Agonist, 2005) was released by Mike Paradinas' Planet Mu label, more commonly associated with the IDM scene.  Unsatisfied with the possibilities of conventional DJing, Exile programmed his own performance tools (at first using Pure Data and running into difficulties, he then switched to Reaktor) to allow improvisational live sets, which led to official work for Native Instruments.  In 2009 he contributed a cover of a Jamie Lidell song to the Warp20 (Recreated) compilation. He also toured the US in late 2009 supporting and collaborating live with Imogen Heap.  In 2012, at Sonar Festival in Barcelona, he teamed up with Jamie Lidell, DJ Shiftee, Mr. Jimmy and Jeremy Ellis to form Mostly Robot, a new collaborative project.  In 2016, he launched Endlesss, a collaborative music-making app inspired by his Flow Machine, which he had previously used in live performances. A desktop version of Endlesss was released in 2020.

Mechazilla is designed to catch and handle the first stage of SpaceX's Starship, known as the Super Heavy Booster, upon its return after launch. This catching mechanism aims to eliminate the need for landing legs on the booster, thereby reducing mass, complexity, and potentially turnaround time between launches. Mechanism:  The tower features two large mechanical arms, often referred to as "chopsticks," which are capable of catching the Super Heavy Booster. These arms can position the booster for stacking with the Starship upper stage before launch and catch it upon its return. The system involves a complex coordination of hydraulic systems, steel cables, and a heavy-duty draw works (a winch-like mechanism) to lift, maneuver, and secure the massive rocket components. Code Drama is coined by Mearaf Tadewos Tiranchie.  It's a witty name given to the phenomenon in the programing ecology where the code you wrote, optimized, tested and deployed and have been functioning well for a while before but now it doesn't work properly, error logs don't speak your language anymore, the debugging process is getting very confusing and stressful and your are questioning you're decisions in life.  Having worked in building different APIs interacting with third parties or SDKs and interacting with APIs from the front end, using libraries and dependency injections in codes, trying to meet deadlines, etc... I sure i countered this phenomenon several times in my 12+ years of learning and building with code including university.  So, to sweeten up the reference and our memories of this rather gruelling experiences, I decided to coin it in a little witty way and called it _> code drama; because, let's be honest it looks like a dram, some times it is as though code has its own life :)  Well, it has its own technical intricacies causing that behind the scenes, that can be us simple us library updates or some where in the jungle of the program a dependency function is depreciated or many other response. And these experiences far from fun for me, i want to be efficient, so going back at things again and again for things like that feels wasteful, and draining, most of makes me go "Why? Whhhhyyyy? for the love of goodness, can i just go back to my solving the actual problem task pleeeeaasse?" hahaha.  I want the world share a light hearted jokes on some sides of our jobs, because who said who should be grumpy all the time :) Smile, it looks good you ;)

ENS (Ethereum Name Service) uses .eth as a TLD. It's similar to traditional TLDs but operates on the Ethereum blockchain. This means that .eth names are secured and managed using cryptocurrency technology.  Essentially, .eth is like a decentralized .com for the Web3 world.
